``python\nfrom typing import List\nfrom collections import Counter\nfrom math import inf\n\nclass Solution:\n    def smallestRange(self, nums: List[List[int]]) -> List[int]:\n        t = [(x, i) for i, v in enumerate(nums) for x in v]\n        t.sort()\n        cnt = Counter()\n        ans = [-inf, inf]\n        j = 0\n        for i, (b, v) in enumerate(t):\n            cnt[v] += 1\n            while len(cnt) == len(nums):\n                a = t[j][0]\n                x = b - a - (ans[1] - ans[0])\n                if x < 0 or (x == 0 and a < ans[0]):\n                    ans = [a, b]\n                w = t[j][1]\n                cnt[w] -= 1\n                if cnt[w] == 0:\n                    cnt.pop(w)\n                j += 1\n        return ans\n```\n\nThis solution uses a flattened list of all elements from the input lists, along with their original list indices. It sorts this list and then uses a sliding window approach with a counter to find the smallest range that includes at least one element from each of the input lists. The counter keeps track of how many lists are represented in the current window. When all lists are represented, it attempts to shrink the window from the left to find the smallest possible range.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}